One use of delta can be thought of like this:

Imagine a piece of code that monitors some value (say, Machine Operating
Temperature). If the temperature is out of a certain range, an alert gets
sounded.

If you&#39;ve got a test that exercises the machine, you can add a test like
this:
  assert(!machine.isInAlertState());
  assertEquals(MIDDLE_OF_THE_SAFE_TEMPERATURE_ZONE,
machine.getTemperature(), HALF_THE_SIZE_OF_THE_ZONE);

Alternatively:

Imagine a machine that inspects items for quality. For simplicity, we&#39;ll
assume something easy, like it&#39;s verifying a piece of wood is of certain
dimensions, with some tolerance (usually small). You can test the code like
this:

  int value = obtainValue();
  assertEquals(EXPECTED_SIZE, value, TOLERANCE);
  assert(machine.passesQualityCheck(value);

Finally, of course, there&#39;s the simplistic answer that floating point
operations aren&#39;t precise. You can&#39;t always be 100% certain that f1 + f2 =
f3, due to rounding errors (especially if any of the values are themselves
derived). The delta allows you to state the degree of error.

Essentially, you use the delta argument whenever you testing an expression
of the form:
  x = y +/- z  (that&#39;s a plus-minus, BTW... the plus should be over the
minus sign).

Robert.

